    "analysis": "Previous step loaded and summarized metric.csv and trace.csv. Metric data contains 45,189 rows spanning 2020-05-23 00:00 to 2020-05-23 00:30 (Asia/Shanghai) across 56 distinct cmdb_id values (examples: db_001..db_006...). Top metric KPIs include Send_total, Disk_io_util, Disk_rd_ios, Processor_load_5_min, Outgoing_network_traffic, etc. A metric sample shows db_001 rows for ACS, AIOS, AWS, CPU_Used_Pct, CPU_free_pct at 2020-05-23 00:00. Trace data contains 6,240 rows spanning 2020-05-23 00:00 to 2020-05-23 00:29 (Asia/Shanghai) across 10 distinct cmdb_id values (examples: docker_001..docker_004...). Top trace names include trace.self.jdbc.*, trace.self.local.*, trace.self.csf.*, and traces from os_022.remoteprocess. Traces show docker_001 calling os_022 remoteprocess with measurable duration and row_count. From these summaries we now need to detect anomalies: compute global thresholds per component-KPI across full available series (not limited to incident window), then inspect points inside the incident window (May 23, 2020 00:00 to 00:30 Asia/Shanghai) to find anomalies. The next step is to compute global P95 and P5 for each component-KPI (metric: cmdb_id + kpi_name; trace: cmdb_id + trace_name) using the full series in the files, then count anomalies in the incident window (both high-side breaches >P95 and low-side breaches <P5). We will request compact top candidate lists only (top 20) with earliest anomaly timestamps and simple severity measures.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and trace.csv, do the following (Executor should perform numeric thresholding and timestamp filtering):\n1) For metric.csv: for each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global P95 and P5 using all available rows for that series. Then filter the series to the incident window from \"2020-05-23 00:00:00+08\" to \"2020-05-23 00:30:00+08\" and compute for each series: total points in-window, count of points > P95, count of points < P5, earliest timestamp in-window where either >P95 or <P5 occurred (if none, null), max value in-window, min value in-window, and if P95>0 compute max_exceed_ratio = (max_in_window - P95)/P95 else null. Return the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) sorted by max(count>p95, count< p5) descending. Output compact table columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, global_p5, points_in_window, count_gt_p95, count_lt_p5, earliest_anom_ts, max_in_window, min_in_window, max_exceed_ratio. Limit rows to 20.\n2) For trace.csv: perform the same procedure per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using full series to compute global P95 and P5, then analyze the same incident window (start \"2020-05-23 00:00:00+08\", end \"2020-05-23 00:30:00+08\"). Return top 20 trace series sorted by max(count>p95, count< p5) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, global_p5, points_in_window, count_gt_p95, count_lt_p5, earliest_anom_ts, max_in_window, min_in_window, max_exceed_ratio. \nKeep outputs compact (max 20 rows each). Store full intermediate tables in kernel variables but do not print them. If any series has zero points in-window, include it only if count_gt_p95 or count_lt_p5 > 0; otherwise exclude it from the returned top list."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous anomaly scan, several series show anomalies in the incident window. The most significant deviation is at service-level component db_001: LFSync_Per_Sec has an extreme max_exceed_ratio (~68x) with earliest anomaly at 2020-05-23 00:00:00+08. Other db_001 KPIs (LFParaWrite_Per_Sec, DbTime, Exec_Per_Sec, Call_Per_Sec) also show breaches during the window. Trace anomalies (docker_001) exist but their severity ratios are much smaller. According to the rules, when multiple faulty components exist at different levels, the fault with the most significant deviation from its threshold (>>50%) indicates the root-cause level. Therefore db_001 is the leading root-cause candidate and the likely occurrence time is at or near 2020-05-23 00:00:00+08. However, we must confirm that db_001 has a sustained fault (consecutive anomalous points) and identify the exact first anomalous timestamp and fault duration across related DB KPIs before finalizing the root cause reason. Currently the underlying reason is unclear from metrics alone (could be DB shutdown/restart or heavy fsync activity); traces and logs may be required to pick between the provided reason labels (CPU fault, network delay/loss, db connection limit, db close).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For cmdb_id = 'db_001', extract metric rows within the incident window 2020-05-23 00:00:00+08 to 2020-05-23 00:30:00+08 for these KPI names: LFSync_Per_Sec, LFParaWrite_Per_Sec, DbTime, Exec_Per_Sec, Call_Per_Sec, ACS. For each KPI do the following using the full-series global thresholds (compute P95 and P5 from all available rows of that KPI for db_001 before filtering):\n1) Return a compact summary table (one row per KPI) with columns: kpi_name, global_p95, global_p5, points_in_window, count_gt_p95, count_lt_p5, earliest_breach_ts (first in-window ts where >P95 or <P5), longest_consecutive_breach_length (max run length of consecutive in-window points breaching >P95 or <P5), max_in_window, min_in_window, max_exceed_ratio (if global_p95>0 else null).\n2) Also return the raw in-window rows for each KPI but limit to at most 31 rows per KPI (full 1-min resolution is fine) sorted by timestamp so we can inspect exact sequence; include columns timestamp, ts_dt, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, and a boolean flag breach_type with values 'gt_p95', 'lt_p5', or 'normal'.\nKeep outputs compact and bounded. Store full intermediate tables in kernel variables but only print the requested compact summary and the per-KPI in-window rows (max 31 each)."
}

